    "Explain idempotency in the context of REST APIs. Why is it important, and which HTTP methods are considered idempotent?",
    "**Answer:** An operation is idempotent if executing it multiple times produces the same result as executing it once. In REST APIs, this means a client can safely retry a request without causing unintended side effects. It's important for reliability and fault tolerance in distributed systems. HTTP methods considered idempotent are GET, PUT, DELETE, and HEAD. POST is generally not idempotent.",
    "**Intention:** To assess knowledge of RESTful principles and how to design reliable APIs."
